# n1d configuration — copy to .env and adjust, or export these in your shell.
# (n1d reads process.env directly; it does not auto-load a .env file. Use your
#  shell, a process manager, or `env $(cat .env | xargs) node n1d.mjs`.)

# HTTP port to listen on.
PORT=8787

# Bind address. Defaults to 127.0.0.1 (localhost only). To allow phone access over
# a private Tailscale tailnet, set this to 0.0.0.0 — and ONLY on a tailnet you fully
# trust: n1d runs an agent with shell access, so never expose it on an untrusted network.
# N1_BIND=0.0.0.0

# Claude model id passed to the `claude` CLI.
N1_MODEL=claude-opus-4-8

# Path to the agent methodology handbook (reloaded per request).
# Default: ../agent/handbook.md (relative to n1d.mjs).
# N1_HANDBOOK=/absolute/path/to/handbook.md

# Optional: directory of extra JSON data sources to expose in the data catalog.
# Each *.json file that is an array of records, plus an optional sensing event
# log (array of { modality, timestamp, payload }), becomes a queryable source.
# Purely env-driven: if unset, the catalog just contains phone-provided sources.
# N1_EXTRA_SOURCES_DIR=/absolute/path/to/data-store

# Optional: name of the sensing event-log file inside N1_EXTRA_SOURCES_DIR.
# Default: sensing.json
# N1_SENSING_FILE=sensing.json
